<HEADLINE>
<P>
INSIDE THE MOSQUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE GUNMAN 
</P>
<P>
 Dr. Baruch Goldstein 
</P>
<P>
 Age: 38 
</P>
<P>
 Occupation: Physician 
</P>
<P>
 Home: Kiryat Arba settlement; moved to Israel 11 years ago from Brooklyn New 
York 
</P>
<P>
 Possible motive: Member of the extremist anti-Arab Kach movement founded by 
the late Rabbi Meir Kahane, who was assassinated in New York in November, 1990. 
Palestinian radicals killed friends of Goldstein's in December. HIS ARSENAL 
</P>
<P>
 Pistol 
</P>
<P>
 Hand grenades 
</P>
<P>
 Israeli-made Galil assault rifle THE ATTACK 
</P>
<P>
 Time: About 5:45 a.m. local time 
</P>
<P>
 Place: The Ibrahim Mosque in the city of Hebron, packed with 600 worshipers 
for Ramadan prayers. Ibrahim Mosque is located in the Cave of the Patriarchs, a 
2,000-year-old shrine that is believed to be the burial place of the patriarch 
Abraham, a holy figure to Jews, Christians and Muslims. HOW IT HAPPENED 
</P>
<P>
 1. Wearing a military uniform, the gunman slips past guards 
</P>
<P>
 2. He stands near the only entrance and opens fire on the back rows of 
worshipers as they kneel, heads to the floor, for dawn prayers. Israel radio 
said the gunman changed ammunition clips several times, and one witnesses said 
he hurled grenades. 
</P>
<P>
 3. The gunman dies after the attack, overpowered and killed by Arabs. THE 
REACTION 
</P>
<P>
 Clashes erupt between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers. Most of the violence 
is around Hebron, a city of 50,000. 
</P>
<P>
 Israeli army pours extra troops into the occupied lands and clamps a curfew on 
Hebron. It also seals off the Gaza Strip and bans Palestinians under age 40 
from entering Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
 In Jerusalem, thousands riot afterward, throwing stones at police, who respond 
with tear gas. THE RIFLE 
</P>
<P>
 Firing rate: 750 rounds per minute 
</P>
<P>
 Capacity: 35 bullets 
</P>
<P>
 Manufacturer: TASS Israel Industries Inc. 
</P>
<P>
 Used by: Israeli forces and other armies 
</P>
<P>
 SOURCES: The Associated Press, the New Columbia Encyclopedia, the Random House 
Encyclopedia 
</P>
