<HEADLINE>
<P>
FEMALE PITCHER ESCAPES TROUBLE IN 10-1 VICTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN BECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Southern California College's Ila Borders, the first woman to pitch in a 
college baseball game, got into her first collegiate jam Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Borders, struggling with her control in the third inning of Vanguards' home 
game against Concordia, threw three consecutive balls to T.J. Wilcoxson with 
the bases loaded.Each errant pitch intensified the volume of the razzing from 
the Concordia dugout. 
</P>
<P>
 But after Borders ran the count to 3 and 2, Wilcoxson hit a soft liner up the 
middle that SCC shortstop Jason Brissey fielded on one hop and threw to first 
for the out. 
</P>
<P>
 Borders got into trouble in several other innings, but was good enough to help 
the Vanguards to a 10-1 victory in a round-robin game of the SCC tournament. 
MARTIN BECK 
</P>
</TEXT>
