<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCC'S BORDERS GAINS VICTORY NO. 2; BASEBALL: FRESHMAN GETS INTO A COUPLE JAMS, 
BUT SHE GOES 6 2/3 INNINGS IN 10-1 VICTORY OVER CONCORDIA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN BECK, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Southern California College's Ila Borders, the first woman to pitch in a 
college baseball game, got into her first collegiate jam Friday at SCC. 
</P>
<P>
 Borders, struggling with her control in the third inning against Concordia, 
threw three consecutive balls to T.J. Wilcoxson with the bases loaded in a 
scoreless game. Each errant pitch intensified the volume of the razzing from 
the Concordia dugout. 
</P>
<P>
 Time for Borders to fold? 
</P>
<P>
 Not this time. After Borders ran the count to 3 and 2, Wilcoxson hit a soft 
liner up the middle that shortstop Jason Brissey fielded on one hop and threw 
to first for the out. 
</P>
<P>
 Borders got into trouble in several other innings and afterward she admitted 
her stuff was sub-par, but it was good enough to help the Vanguards win, 10-1, 
in a round-robin game of the SCC tournament. 
</P>
<P>
 Concordia (2-6) never was able to solve the SCC left-hander. Borders gave up 
three hits and an unearned run in 6 2/3 innings. She walked five, had a wild 
pitch and struck out one. 
</P>
<P>
 Concordia loaded the bases again in the fourth, this time with one out. But 
Borders got Chris Kindreich to ground to second -- SCC almost turned a double 
play -- scoring Concordia's run, and Alex Vicario grounded to Borders to end 
the half inning. 
</P>
<P>
 SCC (4-6), which beat Claremont-Mudd, 12-1, in Borders' first start Feb. 15, 
again gave the freshman from Whittier Christian High plenty of support. The 
Vanguards scored two in the third and two in the fourth, giving Borders a 5-1 
lead. They added two in the seventh and three in the eighth after Borders had 
been replaced by Brissey in the top of the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
 Augie Pena had three hits, including a two-run homer, and four runs batted in. 
</P>
<P>
 Among the more than 200 on hand for the game Friday was a camera crew from a 
Japanese television station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
