<HEADLINE>
<P>
PARENTS OF SLAIN WOMAN SUE HER LOVER; COURTS: BUSINESSMAN SHOULD HAVE 
ANTICIPATED HIS WIFE'S POTENTIAL FOR VIOLENCE AGAINST HIS MISTRESS AND THE 
BABY, THEY ASSERT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEN HALL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The parents of a 25-year-old Chinese woman who was slain along with her baby 
son in Mission Viejo last summer have filed suit against her married lover, 
claiming he should have known their relationship would lead to violence. 
</P>
<P>
 Zhuo Chuan Ji and Xiang Lan Liu of Qindao, China, filed a wrongful death 
lawsuit in federal court Feb. 16 seeking $2 million in punitive damages from 
Tseng Jyi (Jim) Peng, 51, a wealthy Taiwanese businessman who was having an 
extramarital affair with their daughter when she was killed. 
</P>
<P>
 Peng's wife, Li Yuan (Lisa) Peng, who was also named in the lawsuit, has been 
charged with the grisly Aug. 17 slayings of Ranbing (Jennifer) Ji and 
5-month-old Kevin Ji at their apartment near Lake Mission Viejo. 
</P>
<P>
 Lisa Peng pleaded innocent to the slayings and is being held without bail in 
County Jail. On Friday, a preliminary hearing was set for April 15 in Municipal 
Court in Laguna Niguel. 
</P>
<P>
 The slayings ended an affair that lasted more than two years between Jim Peng 
and Jennifer Ji, his former executive secretary. It began in China, and 
continued when she moved to Mission Viejo in August, 1992. Kevin Ji was born 
last March at Saddleback Memorial Medical Center in Laguna Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 The lawsuit, filed in U. S. District Court in Los Angeles, alleges that Jim 
Peng should have known of the potential for violence "created by his infidelity 
to his spouse and family." Jim and Lisa Peng have been married for 21 years and 
have two sons, aged 16 and 20. 
</P>
<P>
 The lawsuit also alleges that Peng knew his wife had learned of the affair and 
that she had threatened Ji. Peng was negligent in financing Ji's lifestyle, 
putting her up in an apartment close to his Rancho Santa Margarita home and not 
providing her with adequate security, said Shin P. Yang, a San Gabriel-based 
attorney for the Ji family. 
</P>
<P>
 "There were a number of encounters" between Ji and Lisa Peng, Yang said. "It's 
not confirmed how many. We know they met at least once." 
</P>
<P>
 In court for a hearing on his wife's criminal case Friday, Peng declined to 
comment other than to say he considered the lawsuit without merit and a 
publicity stunt. 
</P>
<P>
 Jim Peng is chief executive officer of Ranger Communications, one of the 
world's largest manufacturers of citizens-band radios. He discovered the bodies 
of Jennifer and Kevin Ji Aug. 18, when he returned from a business trip to 
Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
 Jennifer Ji was slumped over a living room couch and had been stabbed at least 
18 times. The baby had been suffocated in his crib in a bedroom. 
</P>
<P>
 Although no weapon has been found, Sheriff's Department investigators arrested 
Lisa Peng five months later based on what they consider a crucial piece of 
evidence -- a DNA sample from a bite mark on Jennifer Ji's left arm -- that 
directly links her to the slayings. 
</P>
<P>
 Prosecutors also said two buttons apparently belonging to Lisa Peng were found 
in the apartment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
